Headlines.SeoHeadline: The Morning Ledger: Banks Change Tune on Corporate Cash
Headlines.Author: David Hall
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: Banks Change Tune on Corporate Cash

PARAGRAPH.#text: Banks are changing their tune on corporate cash. After years of discouraging deposits, banks are making a big effort to attract them, writes CFOJ's Vipal Monga in today's Marketplace section. Looming regulatory changes, which will force banks to hold larger cash reserves, are driving the strategic shift. "Last year, almost every bank had more cash than they knew what to do with," Terry Stack, treasurer at Harman International Industries, tells Monga. "They were being decidedly stingy with the yields they were offering." But now companies are funneling their cash back into U.S. banks, which are offering them a new selection of products designed to appeal to corporate customers and average annual rates of 0.30% on deposits, up from 0.20% last year.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: The Morning Ledger: Banks Change Tune on Corporate Cash

Headlines.Headline: Fresenius SE Raises 2013 Outlook

PARAGRAPH.#text: Fresenius SE & Co. KGaA (FRE.XE) Tuesday raised its full year earnings outlook thanks to growth prospects for the second half and higher second-quarter profit. The group now expects 2013 net profit of 11% to 14% higher on the year in constant currency, compared with its previous expectation of 7% to 12%. Sales rose to 5.1 billion euros ($6.8 billion) in the second quarter from EUR4.82 billion the previous year, and net profit increased to EUR243 million from EUR212 million. The company attributed growth to its broad geographic presence and diversified business.

Headlines.Headline: FMC Purchases Omega-3 Maker Epax for $345 Million

PARAGRAPH.#text: FMC Corp. FMC bought omega-3 producer Epax Nutra Holding III AS for $345 million, helping the chemical company to expand into the high-growth nutraceutical market. Epax makes omega-3 fatty acid concentrates used in nutraceuticals, pharmaceuticals and food, and was part of Trygg Pharma Group AS, an omega-3 pharmaceutical company. FMC's acquisition will include Epax's two production facilities in Alesund, Norway, and Seal Sands, U.K. As a part of the transaction, FMC has entered into a long-term supply agreement with Trygg Pharma to provide Trygg with high-concentration omega-3 fish oil for use as an active pharmaceutical ingredient.

Headlines.SeoHeadline: The Morning Ledger: Spain’s Budget Buys Breathing Room
Headlines.Author: David Hall
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: Spain’s Budget Buys Breathing Room

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Spain appears to have bought itself some time to negotiate terms for an EU bailout after the government unveiled a budget that aims to cut spending, raise taxes and overhaul regulations. It’s the country's fifth round of budget cuts and tax increases in just nine months, the FT notes.
Finance Minister Luis de Guindos said his government still isn’t sure what conditions the EU would impose for a possible bailout -- though we know that Germany wants tough timelines and harsh austerity measures in return for its support. But Prime Minister Mariano Rajoy did promise to implement a long EU wish list of reforms, including loosening labor laws and placing limits on early retirement, the WSJ reports.

Headlines.SeoHeadline: The Morning Ledger: Low Rates Cut Two Ways
Headlines.Author: David Hall
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: Low Rates Cut Two Ways

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Businesses balk at tax proposals. We're not hearing much praise from the business community for President Obama's tax proposals in the State of the Union address. Tom Deas, treasurer of fertilizer maker FMC Corp., told us the president's call for a minimum tax on overseas profits could make American multinationals less competitive. "If it's demonstrably better for a U.S. company that makes products overseas to place factories near their customers," it shouldn't be penalized for making that business decision, he said. Snap-On CEO Nicholas Pinchuk told the Journal's John Bussey that he liked the proposal to ease the tax burden for domestic manufacturers, but Obama "seemed to mention several new regulations even as he spoke of reduction." And the former CFO of a large consumer products company suggested that rather than penalizing companies for offshoring jobs, the government should use tax policy to incentivize job creation in the U.S. "Our government must recognize we live in a world economy, not a U.S. economy," he said.
That's a message Corporate America is going to have to make forcefully next month when the Treasury Department outlines corporate-tax code changes. The WSJ says the administration understands the "political challenges of crafting tax changes. But part of their strategy is to begin negotiations with Republicans and business groups now so changes might be added at the end of the year when Congress decides how to address the expiring Bush-era tax cuts."

Headlines.BodyHeadline: The Morning Ledger: Low Rates Cut Two Ways

and Merck

Headlines.Headline: FMC 4Q Profit Rises 34% On Fewer Charges, Higher Margins

#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES FMC Corp.'s

fourth-quarter profit climbed 34% as the company recorded fewer charges, and lower costs helped improve margins. Shares were up 1.2%, to $51.40, in after-hours trading, as revenue topped analysts' expectations. #text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES FMC Corp.'s

unit, FMC Wyoming Corp., will increase list and off-list prices by $50 a short ton for all grades of soda ash.
